<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910531-0008</DOCNO><DOCID>910531-0008.</DOCID><HL>   Kouri Capital Sues   Helsinki Bank, Saying   It Backed Out of Pact</HL><DATE>05/31/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   C.KOP</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)</IN><RE>CONNECTICUT (CT)FINLAND (FI)NEW YORK (NY)</RE><LP>   NEW YORK -- Kouri Capital Inc. filed a lawsuit againstKansallis-Osake-Pankki, accusing the Helsinki-based bank ofbacking out of a 10-year agreement to provide $600 million infinancing.   Kouri is seeking damages of $148.8 million, mostly forfees and profits that the Greenwich, Conn.-based investmentfirm claims it would have received on five projects that wereto be financed under the agreement.</LP><TEXT>   The lawsuit said the agreement was reached in June 1990between Kouri's chairman, Pentti J.K. Kouri, and officials ofthe bank, known as KOP. Mr. Kouri, a former economicsprofessor from Finland, also is a plaintiff in the lawsuit.   Mr. Kouri, who has been an adviser to many Finnishbusinesses, formerly controlled a 6% stake in KOP and wasconsidered an ally of the bank for several years. The last ofhis stake in KOP was sold in September.   In the lawsuit, filed in federal court in Manhattan, Mr.Kouri said KOP sought his help, starting in 1986, in severalcommercial enterprises. The lawsuit said the bank and Mr.Kouri formed several general partnerships through which theyinvested in Finnish companies' securities.   The lawsuit said that KOP was to receive half of thepartnership's profits, although the bank wasn't actuallynamed as a partner. The lawsuit accuses the bank ofmisrepresenting in its public financial reports tens ofmillions of dollars of income from the partnerships.   The lawsuit also seeks an accounting of money paid out bythe partnerships, claiming that Mr. Kouri didn't receive allof his share.   A spokesman for KOP's U.S. branch declined to comment. Anofficial of the bank in Helsinki couldn't be reached forcomment.</TEXT></DOC>